```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  // Only check for divisors up to the square root of num
  for (let i = 2; i * i <= num; i++) {
    if (num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}

function printPrimesFromArray(numbers) {
  if (numbers.length !== 5) {
    console.error('The array must contain exactly 5 numbers.');
    return;
  }

  numbers.forEach(number => {
    if (isPrime(number)) {
      console.log(number);
    }
  });
}

// Example usage:
printPrimesFromArray([11, 18, 23, 28, 29]);
```

This code consists of two functions:

1. `isPrime(num)`: This function checks if a single number is prime. It returns `true` if the number is prime, otherwise `false`. A number is considered prime if it's greater than 1 and has no divisors other than 1 and itself.

2. `printPrimesFromArray(numbers)`: This function takes an array of numbers as an argument, checks if the array has exactly 5 numbers, and uses the `isPrime` function to determine if any of the numbers are prime. If a prime number is found, it's printed to the console.

Please note that this function will immediately log an error to the console if the input array does not contain exactly 5 numbers.

